         <head><title type="main" rend="center">The Bowl. <emph rend="italic"
                  >Anacreontic</emph>.<emph rend="super">1, </emph><note type="head" place="bottom"
                     ><emph rend="super">1</emph> Published in <emph rend="italic">City Gazette and
                     Daily Advertiser</emph> [Charleston, SC] (February 27, 1796), p. 3.</note><emph rend="super">2</emph><note
                  type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph rend="super">2</emph> In English poetry, short
                  lyrical pieces consisting of seven-syllable lines. First used by Abraham Cowley in
                  1656, “Anacreontic” references the Greek poet Anacreon whose poems Cowley
                  paraphrased in <emph rend="italic">Poems</emph>.</note></title></head>

         <lg type="stanza">
            <l rend="indent" n="1">Artist, form a spacious bowl,</l>
            <l> Fit to let the liquor roll</l>
            <l>Like the billows of the sea;</l>
            <l>Artist, form this bowl for me.</l>
            <l n="5">Round the silver brim entwine</l>
            <l>Wreathing clusters of the vine,</l>
            <l>Shew with smiling easy grace</l>
            <l>Bacchus<emph rend="super">3</emph><note type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph
                     rend="super">3</emph> God of wine.</note> of the jolly face.</l>
            <l>Let Anacreon<emph rend="super">4</emph><note type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph
                     rend="super">4</emph> Greek lyric poet, notable for his drinking songs.</note>
               there be plac’d</l>
            <l n="10">With a crown of laurel<emph rend="super">5</emph><note type="gloss"
                  place="bottom"><emph rend="super">5</emph> Symbol of honor for poets and
                  heroes.</note> grac’d,</l>
            <l>Singing to his sportive lyre</l>
            <l>Joys that love and wine inspire.</l>
            <l>Bacchus, press the purple vine,</l>
            <l>Fill my cup with rosy wine;</l>
            <l n="15">Then I’ll raise the song with glee,</l>
            <l>Praising wine and praising thee. </l>

         </lg>
